<p>When the content of a page has expired or it is not relevant anymore, and a new version is available in a different URL, it is common that the web administrator creates rules so the old URL redirects to the new content URL.</p>
<p>One IIS module used to do this task is the <a href="https://www.iis.net/downloads/microsoft/url-rewrite" target="_blank">IIS URL Rewrite</a>&nbsp;which allows creating rules to generate URLs that can be easier for users to remember, simple for search engines to index, allow URLs to follow a consistent and canonical hostname format, and also redirect to a new URL.</p>
<p>However, the rules have to be&nbsp;created in the web.config file, which means that the web administrator cannot create or modify a rule without restarting the application instance.</p>
<p>Fortunately for Sitecore applications, there is a module available in the marketplace that allows creating the same rules that can be created with the IIS URL Rewrite module, its name is <a href="https://marketplace.sitecore.net/Modules/U/Url_Rewrite.aspx?sc_lang=en">URL Rewrite Module</a>.&nbsp;With this module, you can create the following rules:</p>
<ul>
<li>Simple Redirect<br />Allows you to specify a regular expression match condition and a redirect target URL. It will always use a 301 redirect set to not cache.</li>
<li>Inbound Rule<br />Allows you to set a regular expression to match on the path of a URL. Supports regular expression capture groups the same way that IIS UrlRewrite module does.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Installation</strong></p>
<p>Download the module from the downloads section of the <a href="https://marketplace.sitecore.net/Modules/U/Url_Rewrite.aspx?sc_lang=en">URL Rewrite Module</a>&nbsp;page. Then, install the module using the Installation Wizard.&nbsp;Finally, publish the&nbsp;<strong><em>/</em></strong>sitecore<strong><em>/system/Modules/Url Rewrite</em></strong> item, be sure you select&nbsp;<label id="PublishChildren_label" for="PublishChildren"><em>Publish subitems</em> and <em>P</em></label><em><label id="PublishRelatedItems_label" for="PublishRelatedItems">ublish related items.</label></em></p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></p>
<h2>Usage</h2>
<p>Once the module is installed, there is a folder in the Sitecore/Content/ level which contains some&nbsp;rewrite items.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></p>
<h3>Simple redirect creation</h3>
<p>To create a simple redirect, right click at a folder where you want to create the rewrite rule and select Simple Redirect.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></p>
<p>Then, modify the Path and Target fields. The Target link can be an internal or external resource.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></p>
<p>Then, save it and publish it. Once it is published, if the user visits the http://sc800/developer path (sc800 is the&nbsp;domain name of the local instance&nbsp;used&nbsp;for this example), the request will be redirected to <a href="https://dev.sitecore.net">https://dev.sitecore.net</a>.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" /></p>
<h3>Constraints</h3>
<ul>
<li>The paths added in the&nbsp;IgnoreUrlPrefixes setting of Sitecore are also ignored by&nbsp;this module. This means, for instance, if the&nbsp;IgnoreUrlPrefixes setting has a value like&nbsp; <em>/</em>sitecore<em>/</em>, and the path you set is "sitecore", then it would not be redirected.</li>
</ul>
<p>In the next post, I will show how to create more complex and different rules using&nbsp;Inbound Rules.</p>
<p>That's it for today.</p>
